    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "e710e5b0_5266c93b",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 10,
      "author": {
        "id": 5633
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-01-15T17:06:45Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e Emulated scissor clears went from 300ns to 3.3us\n\u003e Emulated full screen clears went from 80ns to 290ns\n\nSo the runtime for scissored clear increased by 3000ns (10x), and for fullscreen clear, 210ns (only 2.5x). I wonder why a partial clear is so much more expensive? In both cases aren\u0027t we just sending a single quad to the GPU? I\u0027m not very concerned about ClearBench perf, but I would like to understand the discrepancy between these two numbers. It seems like there might be something else slowing down partial clears in addition to normal Op overhead.",
      "parentUuid": "4b20c5a0_2f039769",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 9,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 10,
        "endChar": 63
      },
      "revId": "18132270c43a8e2ad3533c46d8498280ebe8d24c",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d0d96e06_c28ef131",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 10,
      "author": {
        "id": 8341
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-01-15T17:19:47Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "That timing measurement was misleading. The clear benchmark I was using in timing did not flush between clears, so when the GrClearOp was being used, every single loop would get consolidated into a single, final operation (its batching logic checks to see if it overwrites the prior clear, even if it was a partial clear). \n\nWhen switching to the GrFillRectOp, this consolidation could not happen for partial clears (not implemented in GrFillRectOps\u0027 batching logic). However, fullscreen clears remained closer to original performance because it could reset the op list to only hold on to a single op.\n\nI have a short CL that fixes the benchmark, and after rerunning nanobench, both the desktop and Nexus5 saw a more consistent increase time.  Additionally, the fullscreen clear as draw takes longer than a partial clear as draw on both devices, which I would expect when forced to go through regular rasterization.",
      "parentUuid": "e710e5b0_5266c93b",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 9,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 10,
        "endChar": 63
      },
      "revId": "18132270c43a8e2ad3533c46d8498280ebe8d24c",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "89b849a7_1490e064",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 10,
      "author": {
        "id": 5633
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-01-15T18:00:52Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Got it! That makes sense.\n\nFinal question, I promise :-) If fullscreen clear takes longer, that would suggest we are GPU bound. But if we are GPU bound, then why is there a small slowdown still?",
      "parentUuid": "d0d96e06_c28ef131",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 9,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 10,
        "endChar": 63
      },
      "revId": "18132270c43a8e2ad3533c46d8498280ebe8d24c",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "be2ab07c_b5906d51",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 10,
      "author": {
        "id": 8341
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-01-15T18:50:06Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "So I do not have a complete answer to that question, but when running rectangle benchmarks, I do see an increase in render time correlating with an increase in rectangle area. Since this CL moves the clears over to GrFillRectOp, and it seems to be GPU bound, that would explain the trend shown in the clear benchmarks.\n\nNow, why that op would be GPU bound is curious and deserves some more investigation (I did confirm, the size-based slowdown exists at tip of tree too).",
      "parentUuid": "89b849a7_1490e064",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 9,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 10,
        "endChar": 63
      },
      "revId": "18132270c43a8e2ad3533c46d8498280ebe8d24c",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
